We'll take questions.

00:39:59.737 --> 00:40:01.820
The price of asking a
question is you should first

00:40:01.820 --> 00:40:03.270
introduce yourself.

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:04.550
- My name is David Arnold.

00:40:04.550 --> 00:40:05.450
Good afternoon.

00:40:05.450 --> 00:40:12.040
Who was holding out on
the 1982 treaty and why?

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:17.230
- There are a lot of
members of Congress

00:40:17.230 --> 00:40:20.860
who believe that the
convention is not in the best

00:40:20.860 --> 00:40:24.460
interests of the United States.

00:40:24.460 --> 00:40:26.560
I think, and I'm just
going to generalize here

00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:30.130
because I don't want to point
to any particular individual.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:33.040
I'm just going to generally
talk about some of the concerns

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:34.240
that I've heard.

00:40:34.240 --> 00:40:37.570
The first is I think there's
some misinformation out there.

00:40:37.570 --> 00:40:40.780
The problems that plague
the 1982 convention

00:40:40.780 --> 00:40:43.900
are still talked about as
reasons why we shouldn't join.

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:46.369
This convention is modified
by the Part 11 agreement.

00:40:46.369 --> 00:40:48.160
So there's just
fundamental misinformation.

00:40:48.160 --> 00:40:51.100
People talk about forced
technology sharing.

00:40:51.100 --> 00:40:53.170
That's resolved.

00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:57.190
There are other people who
don't like the mandatory dispute

00:40:57.190 --> 00:40:58.900
resolution mechanisms.

00:40:58.900 --> 00:41:01.900
However, if you look at
a lot of US agreements,

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:03.700
they have dispute
resolution mechanisms.

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:05.722
And so, I'm not sure
why we're shying away

00:41:05.722 --> 00:41:07.930
from dispute resolution,
especially when we carve out

00:41:07.930 --> 00:41:10.000
military activities,
law enforcement

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.420
activities, and other things
that just aren't going to be

00:41:13.420 --> 00:41:16.240
subject to dispute resolution.

00:41:16.240 --> 00:41:19.930
I think there is some
concern about paying

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:27.780
royalties for exploration in
the extent of continental shelf.

00:41:27.780 --> 00:41:29.980
There's a scheme set up
through the convention

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:32.020
that if you have an extended
continental shelf, although you

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:34.050
get sovereign rights to that
extent of continental shelf

00:41:34.050 --> 00:41:35.425
and I should say
parenthetically,

00:41:35.425 --> 00:41:38.200
we believe that if we
follow the procedures

00:41:38.200 --> 00:41:39.870
in the convention
which we now hold

00:41:39.870 --> 00:41:40.890
is customary international law.

00:41:40.890 --> 00:41:43.098
But if we went through the
process and the convention

00:41:43.098 --> 00:41:45.180
and secured the greatest
legal footing possible,

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:47.850
we could claim an extended
continental shelf that's

00:41:47.850 --> 00:41:49.510
probably twice the
size of California

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:52.140
or at least the size of
California-- it's huge--

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:54.030
and we would get
sovereign rights.

00:41:54.030 --> 00:41:56.320
And that means the ability
to explore and exploit

00:41:56.320 --> 00:41:58.890
those resources
beyond 200 miles.

00:41:58.890 --> 00:42:01.870
But the convention
sets up a system

00:42:01.870 --> 00:42:06.367
where you have to pay a
certain percentage of royalties

00:42:06.367 --> 00:42:07.950
to the international
seabed authority,

00:42:07.950 --> 00:42:09.410
and people just don't like that.

00:42:09.410 --> 00:42:12.580
However, those provisions
were negotiated in large part

00:42:12.580 --> 00:42:14.800
by the offshore industry
back during the conventions

00:42:14.800 --> 00:42:16.120
negotiations.

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:19.390
They have no problem
with the royalty scheme.

00:42:19.390 --> 00:42:21.990
In fact, the royalty scheme
only kicks in five years

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.010
after you start production.

00:42:24.010 --> 00:42:26.830
A lot of wells are pretty
much exhausted by the time

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:28.540
you get to five years.

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:33.580
So those are just a few
reasons, and again there's just

00:42:33.580 --> 00:42:36.307
some bad information out there.

00:42:36.307 --> 00:42:38.890
Beyond just stale information,
just bad information out there,

00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:40.848
for example I've heard
some people say it would

00:42:40.848 --> 00:42:43.750
create a United Nations Navy.

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:46.140
There ain't nothing I've
seen that says that.

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:49.290
It says that no military
activities will be

00:42:49.290 --> 00:42:50.540
subject to dispute resolution.

00:42:50.540 --> 00:42:52.150
We know that's not true.

00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:54.010
And I could go on
and on and on, but I

00:42:54.010 --> 00:42:57.550
think what we tried to do a few
years ago when we were trying

00:42:57.550 --> 00:43:01.660
to move it through the Senate
as an administration was

00:43:01.660 --> 00:43:06.190
to correct any misperception
and to focus on what we see

00:43:06.190 --> 00:43:08.430
is large strategic benefits
to the United States,

00:43:08.430 --> 00:43:11.550
such as making sure that
we continue to project

00:43:11.550 --> 00:43:14.100
global leadership
on ocean policy,

00:43:14.100 --> 00:43:16.600
making sure that we can secure
those rights on the strongest

00:43:16.600 --> 00:43:20.320
legal footing possible,
making sure that we can secure

00:43:20.320 --> 00:43:23.260
and perfect title
to those resources

00:43:23.260 --> 00:43:25.660
on an extended
continental shelf.

00:43:25.660 --> 00:43:27.160
- I just want to
add a quick comment

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:28.890
to what the Admiral
said, and that is it

00:43:28.890 --> 00:43:32.470
underscores the significant
voice the nation's military has

00:43:32.470 --> 00:43:34.942
right now on a lot of fronts.

00:43:34.942 --> 00:43:36.400
We have a national
government which

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:39.720
for decades has been
largely paralyzed

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:42.490
by partisanship
and by increasing

00:43:42.490 --> 00:43:45.120
distrust of the government.

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:47.050
The nation's military
has a distinctively

00:43:47.050 --> 00:43:49.720
reliable and credible
voice that can really

00:43:49.720 --> 00:43:52.530
help break some of the logjams
on many of these pressing

00:43:52.530 --> 00:43:54.371
issues.

00:43:54.371 --> 00:43:56.370
- Hi, I'm Peter Girguis
from Harvard University.

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:57.786
Thank you for that presentation.

00:43:57.786 --> 00:43:58.660
I have two questions.

00:43:58.660 --> 00:43:59.970
I'll start with the easy one.

00:43:59.970 --> 00:44:04.660
In light of your commitment to
appropriate resource management

00:44:04.660 --> 00:44:06.700
and environmental
protection security,

00:44:06.700 --> 00:44:10.700
have you considered running
for president-- question one?

00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:16.120
And on a more-- on maybe
a more difficult note,

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:20.370
I've been part of the National
Science Foundation's council

00:44:20.370 --> 00:44:23.350
that oversees the US
academic research fleet.

00:44:23.350 --> 00:44:25.789
And one I can
absolutely corroborate

00:44:25.789 --> 00:44:28.080
what the Rear Admiral said,
and that is the icebreakers

00:44:28.080 --> 00:44:29.530
are a real problem.

00:44:29.530 --> 00:44:31.990
That the US academic
community depends

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:35.490
on those icebreakers for
research in the polar regions,

00:44:35.490 --> 00:44:39.030
and at this point it's
actually embarrassing

00:44:39.030 --> 00:44:40.560
that we're at the
state we're at.

00:44:40.560 --> 00:44:42.101
But the question I
have for you, sir,

00:44:42.101 --> 00:44:44.910
is do you see an opportunity
to have academics engaged

00:44:44.910 --> 00:44:48.330
with your more daily and routine
activities given that we've

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:50.850
lost about a third of our
academic research fleet

00:44:50.850 --> 00:44:52.830
and given that
your ships maintain

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:54.600
a more substantial presence?

00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:58.100
Do you see a way that we can
collaborate across agencies,

00:44:58.100 --> 00:45:00.820
whether it's the US Coast
Guard and the National Science

00:45:00.820 --> 00:45:01.990
Foundation or so on?

00:45:01.990 --> 00:45:03.450
Thank you.

00:45:03.450 --> 00:45:05.200
- Thanks for the question.

00:45:05.200 --> 00:45:07.930
I absolutely do, and
I hope I mentioned

00:45:07.930 --> 00:45:09.430
some of those in my remarks.

00:45:09.430 --> 00:45:12.520
I think it's important for
the scientific community

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:17.160
and the academic community
to help us push technology,

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:18.250
to protect the oceans.

00:45:18.250 --> 00:45:21.490
I mentioned oil spill detection.

00:45:21.490 --> 00:45:24.164
We have real challenges now
with some of the heavier oils

00:45:24.164 --> 00:45:26.080
that are being transported
that actually sink.

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:26.788
They don't float.

00:45:26.788 --> 00:45:29.140
You can skim oil on
top of the surface

00:45:29.140 --> 00:45:32.370
or you can clean it when
it hits the beaches.

00:45:32.370 --> 00:45:35.941
It's hard to clean up oil that
has a specific gravity-- what

00:45:35.941 --> 00:45:36.940
is it, greater than one?

00:45:36.940 --> 00:45:39.370
Somebody help me with science.

00:45:39.370 --> 00:45:40.500
Thank you, whew!

00:45:40.500 --> 00:45:42.240
[LAUGHING]

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:45.600
- Chemistry major.

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:47.910
- But I think the other
thing that's very helpful,

00:45:47.910 --> 00:45:50.243
and I'm going to speak as a
commander of the First Coast

00:45:50.243 --> 00:45:52.990
Guard district who has a large
fisheries responsibility up

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:57.660
here in New England, and that
is to help us really develop

00:45:57.660 --> 00:46:01.080
the kind of metrics that
we need to make sure

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:05.080
that our enforcement
actions are bearing fruit.

00:46:05.080 --> 00:46:07.240
Not in terms of penalizing
the fishing fleet,

00:46:07.240 --> 00:46:12.090
but in terms of
preserving the fish stock.

00:46:12.090 --> 00:46:14.620
Is enforcement having an effect?

00:46:14.620 --> 00:46:17.490
We can do it when we talk
about Coast Guard counterdrug

00:46:17.490 --> 00:46:18.300
efforts.

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:23.787
We know generally how much
cocaine is produced worldwide.

00:46:23.787 --> 00:46:25.120
We know how much we're catching.

00:46:25.120 --> 00:46:27.020
We have good detection
and monitoring

00:46:27.020 --> 00:46:29.530
so we know often
when the bad guys go

00:46:29.530 --> 00:46:32.890
by because we just don't have
the resources to get them.

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:35.910
The equation is a little
bit easier in counterdrug.

00:46:35.910 --> 00:46:38.200
It's not easy when it comes
to fisheries enforcement

00:46:38.200 --> 00:46:39.880
because each fish
stock is different,

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:41.850
each species is different.

00:46:41.850 --> 00:46:45.330
They're migratory and
I'm not sure we've

00:46:45.330 --> 00:46:48.430
got the best possible
handle that we can

00:46:48.430 --> 00:46:53.240
on what the nature
of the problem is.

00:46:53.240 --> 00:46:56.080
I'm responsible for
putting Coast Guard

00:46:56.080 --> 00:47:00.260
resources to use the most
effective way possible.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:02.170
The only way I can
do that is if I

00:47:02.170 --> 00:47:04.300
can circle back
and look at metrics

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:06.402
that say I'm having an effect.

00:47:06.402 --> 00:47:08.110
It's hard for me to
do that in fisheries.

00:47:08.110 --> 00:47:11.680
We're working on it within
the Coast Guard, but, wow,

00:47:11.680 --> 00:47:16.420
wouldn't it help if academia
and scientists joined us

00:47:16.420 --> 00:47:19.510
in that effort?

00:47:19.510 --> 00:47:22.360
- I'm Tanya [? Vartanian. ?]
I'm a musician with interest

00:47:22.360 --> 00:47:25.080
in the sciences.

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:28.720
I was wondering
how much the-- how

00:47:28.720 --> 00:47:33.820
do you reconcile the
military experimentation that

00:47:33.820 --> 00:47:39.250
goes on in the oceans
with preserving

00:47:39.250 --> 00:47:43.060
the acoustical environment of
the sea mammals and other sea

00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:44.560
animals?

00:47:44.560 --> 00:47:48.370
I know there is a conflict
there that sometimes becomes

00:47:48.370 --> 00:47:50.790
the subject of discussion.

00:47:50.790 --> 00:47:54.760
- Yeah, you're not going to like
my answer to this because I'm

00:47:54.760 --> 00:47:57.700
not the expert on
sonars and acoustics

00:47:57.700 --> 00:48:00.600
because no Coast Guard
cutters have sonar.

00:48:00.600 --> 00:48:06.940
We took sonars off years
ago, so we're not the experts

00:48:06.940 --> 00:48:09.040
by any means.

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:11.660
Somebody correct me if the
new cutters have sonar.

00:48:11.660 --> 00:48:13.710
I stand corrected.

00:48:13.710 --> 00:48:17.210
But no, we're not the
experts on acoustics.

00:48:17.210 --> 00:48:19.750
I mean, I listened to
the prior presentation

00:48:19.750 --> 00:48:24.370
with great interest, but it's
not something that we focus on.

00:48:24.370 --> 00:48:28.450
What I found more
applicable to us

00:48:28.450 --> 00:48:32.170
were the commercial
vessel trends transiting

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:34.990
through the right
whale areas, and we

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:37.180
do enforce the
speed restrictions

00:48:37.180 --> 00:48:38.710
to protect the right whales.

00:48:38.710 --> 00:48:39.820
- Thank you.

00:48:39.820 --> 00:48:42.160
- Sorry I didn't have a
better answer for you.

00:48:42.160 --> 00:48:43.610
- Thank you very much.

00:48:43.610 --> 00:48:46.757
- And with that, we'd like to
thank the Admiral, Richard.

00:48:46.757 --> 00:48:49.739
[APPLAUSE]

00:48:52.730 --> 00:48:55.610
So this has been a
delightful symposium

00:48:55.610 --> 00:48:57.740
because of all the
amazing presentations

00:48:57.740 --> 00:48:59.820
and great questions.

00:48:59.820 --> 00:49:03.470
The first one was amazing.

00:49:03.470 --> 00:49:05.240
I was really pleased
to learn about all

00:49:05.240 --> 00:49:06.860
the different
metabolic pathways.

00:49:06.860 --> 00:49:11.340
I will mention that one of the
poster session people, Joey

00:49:11.340 --> 00:49:17.330
Nelson, did her dissertation
on sulfur-- bacteria that uses

00:49:17.330 --> 00:49:19.385
sulfur as an energy source.

00:49:19.385 --> 00:49:20.510
So you may want to see her.

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:24.560
The second panel looks--
it's somewhat sobering

00:49:24.560 --> 00:49:27.530
to look at the effects of
temperature changes, especially

00:49:27.530 --> 00:49:32.480
this number that-- I guess if
30% of the sea ice-- Arctic sea

00:49:32.480 --> 00:49:36.110
ice is left, that means
that 70% has gone away.

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:38.900
And most of what is
remaining is not old ice,

00:49:38.900 --> 00:49:42.590
but it's just new
ice and just seems

00:49:42.590 --> 00:49:45.440
like we're looking
at a disaster there.

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:48.920
It also shows the
incredible heat capacity.

00:49:48.920 --> 00:49:52.610
That little graph that showed
how much of the heat capacity

00:49:52.610 --> 00:49:55.940
is in the atmosphere compared
to how much is in the ocean-- I

00:49:55.940 --> 00:49:58.170
mean, I kind of knew
that conceptually,

00:49:58.170 --> 00:50:00.650
but to see it
displayed was just-- it

00:50:00.650 --> 00:50:01.850
really hit home to me.

00:50:01.850 --> 00:50:04.520
So that was incredible.

00:50:04.520 --> 00:50:08.030
We heard about very detailed
engineering strategies

00:50:08.030 --> 00:50:11.240
about how to mitigate the
risks of sea level rise.

00:50:11.240 --> 00:50:14.570
Because as we heard,
already the sea level rise

00:50:14.570 --> 00:50:16.030
is baked into the atmosphere.

00:50:16.030 --> 00:50:18.470
I mean, we can make choices
now about CO2 emissions,

00:50:18.470 --> 00:50:21.920
but it's coming and so
we have to get prepared

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:24.050
and it's our decision
whether or not

00:50:24.050 --> 00:50:26.480
it's going to get really
bad or whether or not

00:50:26.480 --> 00:50:27.980
it becomes manageable.

00:50:27.980 --> 00:50:31.190
So that was what we saw there.

00:50:31.190 --> 00:50:33.760
And then the third
panel-- again,

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:36.980
the effects of global warming.

00:50:36.980 --> 00:50:40.370
I caught a sea bass over
the summer off of Cape Cod,

00:50:40.370 --> 00:50:42.572
and we looked at it
and said, what's this.

00:50:42.572 --> 00:50:44.030
And we had to get
our little thing.

00:50:44.030 --> 00:50:46.696
And then the first thing he says
was, yeah, it's global warming.

00:50:46.696 --> 00:50:48.550
And then we tossed
it back and I just

00:50:48.550 --> 00:50:50.340
realized it was global warming.

00:50:50.340 --> 00:50:53.930
So, thanks.

00:50:53.930 --> 00:50:58.840
It's impressive the stress that
we're putting on New England

00:50:58.840 --> 00:51:03.400
biomass out there, and
I think next time I

00:51:03.400 --> 00:51:06.020
hear I have to stay away
from a right whale area,

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:07.910
I'll definitely be doing it.

00:51:07.910 --> 00:51:11.050
And finally, I think
with the closing talk

00:51:11.050 --> 00:51:15.380
by the Admiral and just looking
at the diversity of ways

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:17.990
of looking at this,
it just gets me back

00:51:17.990 --> 00:51:20.120
to at least a somewhat
hopeful state.

00:51:20.120 --> 00:51:22.130
I mean, when I was
in the Marshalls,

00:51:22.130 --> 00:51:25.880
as I opened up the talk,
I realized that we really

00:51:25.880 --> 00:51:27.980
are highly dependent on
protecting the ocean,

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:31.220
and all of us have to think
about becoming protectors

00:51:31.220 --> 00:51:33.080
of the ocean because
it's something

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:34.300
that affects all of us.

00:51:34.300 --> 00:51:37.880
And I hope the symposium
today brought home that,

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:40.970
and as you go home you start
to reflect on what you heard

00:51:40.970 --> 00:51:44.000
and how you may
contribute in some way.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:47.270
So thank you all and
enjoy the reception.

00:51:47.270 --> 00:51:50.320
[APPLAUSE]

